description:
Another beauty from the slopes of Penang Hill, Nepenthes albomarignata, or the "White-lipped Pitcher Plant" is unique among carnivorous plants for its specialisation to a single prey taxon. 

The characteristic "white lip" which gives the pitcher plant its name actually consists of small hairs called "trichomes" which grow around the peristome of the trap. These hairs are a unique adaptation that specifically targets termites, which are the plant's preferred prey. Though it is still unknown how the trichomes are able to attract termites, that they are highly effective is already established.

Marlis A. Merbach, a botanist who reflected on these adaptations remarked that "... after a single night - pitchers would fill with termites and their rim hairs would disappear."

Unlike its carnivorous cousins, the Flask-shaped Pitcher Plant (Nepenthes ampullaria) has largely evolved away from a taste for insects. Instead, it is known as a detritivore, meaning that it obtains a majority of its nutrients from decomposing plant matter. 
The uniquely shaped traps of N. ampullaria; with their small, backward facing peristomes, are special adaptions to increase the efficiency of trapping leaf litter as they fall directly from the canopy to the forest floor. The "digestion" of plant matter is then aided by organisms such as insect larvae and bacteria that live in the Pitcher and is absorbed by the plant as ammonium ions.

description:
Nepenthes macrophylla – The Muscle Pitcher of the Mountain

Its massive pitchers rival camping water bottles in size, with rims slick as slides. Insects, frogs, or small animals slip and tumble in—straight into a giant trap. With a deep, wide mouth and a slippery edge, this mountain-top predator means serious business.

A giant, a hunter, a true beast of the peak.

Nepenthes lowii – The Aladdin’s Lamp That Keeps Pets or the Jungle’s Public Toilet?

This pitcher doesn’t hunt insects. Instead, it opens itself as a “rest stop” for birds and squirrels—offering sweet nectar in exchange for... their poop. Like a caretaker feeding animals just to collect their droppings in a giant forest chamber pot, it has evolved from predator to toilet host in one of nature’s wildest twists.

Because poop is life.
